Barack Obama will be the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth US president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The diploma, medal and cheque for $1.4 million will be presented to him, among other things, for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and will have a busy schedule.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time ever the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from 172 individuals and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple's schedule then includes a meeting with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
The visit will culminate in the afternoon during a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, but only the third to receive the award within the Committee's precincts.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would speak about the war in Afghanistan at the award ceremony.
The president does not want to avoid this topic because he is aware that he receives this award by being a president who is fighting a war in two countries at the moment.
He stepped up the war effort just a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, something none of his critics will fail to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish kronor (about 1.1 million Euros).
He plans to donate them to charity, but he has not yet decided which ones.
His busy schedule will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant to accept this price at first.
For example, he mentioned feeling that he did not fully deserve it.
He has also repeated several times that this is not a prize for him alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
As soon as the announcement was made, he said it would be a "call to action" for him.
