United States: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It even becomes comical, the assiduous effort with which Barack Obama, president with the reputation of sage, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he himself considered very simple.
When he finally let his long-awaited doctrine transpire, it turned out that he had copied it with carbon paper since Bush's Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content with using in the text even several times the expression "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward".
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements to an Iraq consumed by civil war as "irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers at present do not mention Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively speaking, he left his successor with a much more favorable final situation than could have been hoped.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the field commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the reluctance of the White House despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but for lack of a better option, he at least defrauded the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to extract the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally counted on 10,000.
What brings the most problems in Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and complete this whole process within three years. The whole Obama doctrine raises more questions than it answers.
Many doubt that a halving will bring the same fruits as the advance in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is the exact opposite — no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders on a day-to-day basis according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing more than window dressing behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
Balancing the interests of various ethnic groups is singularly complex given the lack of clarity about the relationship, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "quick state," which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is perplexing by its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and unrealistic heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "speedy return home" will bring about a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will see it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving towards the negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the tightened sanctions do not have an effect on the Iranians, the Americans will be faced with the very difficult question of solving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Each such solution, however, will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only fuss for Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
