Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Pneumococcal vaccination will reverse old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Voices are already being raised saying that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines the maximum prices for vaccines that health insurance companies will pay.
Specialists also see clearly in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for children in August.
Since January, children born last year from August 2 can be vaccinated against pneumococci free of charge.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of vaccine should be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Already last year, a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococci.
Yet parents paid 1600 crowns or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Experts estimate that every year health insurers spend 300 to 450,000 crowns on vaccine doses.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would need.
Until now, the State has spent about NOK 500,000 per year on all childhood vaccinations.
Reimbursed vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococci are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the meninges and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under 10 years of age caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions regarding a possible vaccination obligation in the future.
From January, it must be paid by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted pneumococcal vaccination.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we were able to impose at least this.
I think this is a direction that must now be followed," Kalovský said.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the process of vaccination against pneumococci.
"We are not considering it at the moment," said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Society of Paediatricians, acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its flaws.
If all children were vaccinated, we could envisage a decrease in vaccination renewals "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional," says Cabrnochová.
Experts predict that by next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Vaccination against pneumococci also marks a break because it is the first vaccination of children that is financed by insurance and not the State.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance companies should free up funds for prevention, saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves
However, this is related to the concerns of practicing paediatricians, who concern the purchase of vaccines.
The original intention was to have vaccines purchased by insurance, with doctors receiving them in the same way as other vaccine products provided by the state.
However, some MEPs feared that this would allow insurance companies to "deduct sums from health insurance".
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to reimburse them.
According to estimates, individual paediatricians will have to invest almost 40,000 crowns per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
