Although officials in a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for files from couples wanting a second child after the campaign launches, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
Huinan commune, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only about 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009 but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in Shanghai's Caolu commune, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally allowed to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have minimum health insurance and government-given life insurance.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners mistakenly view the one-child policy as a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
It's true, we are robbed of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the HR manager, said she only wanted an only child because she was one herself. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us."
We're not used to taking care of someone else and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42, owner of a translation company, puts it more bluntly.
For middle-class couples working together, who lower the birth rate, he says, you have to be selfish to succeed.
People in their 20s and 30s grew up watching their parents struggle in the early days of capitalist China and don't want to have that lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even a single child takes a lot of time from their parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space issues -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you need to write his resume to get a place in the best kindergarten."
Most of his friends are willing to experience it once, Chen says, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to enjoy a higher standard of living, he says.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
UN group has draft plans for emission reductions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- so far characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- returned to the spotlight on Friday, with the release of a document outlining ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations shouldering most of the burden.  in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it illuminated the path to be taken.
But it was seen as an important breakthrough in time-running negotiations, with more than 100 world leaders arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by a special UN working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key questions, including how developed and emerging economies might decrease their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of global temperature increase that policymakers would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Washington Representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change Yvo de Boer described as "the full picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020 by 25 to 45 percent below 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also revived negotiations on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and droughts or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. representative to the climate negotiation, rejected any discussion that would require industrialized countries to reduce greenhouse gases, compared to the voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if they were not funded by developed countries.
This shift is a signal that the Obama administration is becoming tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top U.S. negotiator either lacked "common sense" or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not help China financially to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the world's major powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the US squabbling over each other's obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
It's really a game in which a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who is also climate adviser for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission's climate unit, said the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the entire political process", in part because they are now unified and are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on resolving most of the outstanding issues before heads of government reached agreement.
High-level officials such as India's Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China's Vice Minister stepped off their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and informational conferences, so they could make claims that will be considered over the next week.
The true image of the rally -- in which 13,000 people enter and leave the Palais des congrès every day -- of guitar-playing activists present nightly shows mocking countries they say are betraying each other and that proposals are written and distributed in paper rather than email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the big leagues," said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavy trucks are coming.
In Britain, the first train at 225 km/h will redefine the Monday syndrome
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will blow through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transport revolution in Britain.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 225 km/h, as it runs from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering the 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister for Transport, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes on board the first Javelin commuter train outside London.
He hopes the new service will bring Britain into an international network of fast and reliable trains and link the major conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
Small lost holes will become thriving suburban towns, business travel times will be much shorter, and switching from plane and car to train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing traffic congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties adhere to this project.
But the ten billion pounds needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable planning battle and fears of environmental hazards are likely to put the brakes on Britain's high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will return its document to Lord Adonis on 30 December.
This will allow him to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage planned for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be designed within five metres of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment may be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up to 25 meters from the final route.
HS2 is also expected to present three options for a larger, northbound high-speed network.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred options are put forward in a Y-shaped configuration for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two at or near Birmingham, with a branch going west from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another going northeast, to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
"It looks like this will be the best performance option," said one rail professional.
When this is over, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which won't open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, up from the current one-hour journey.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making the UK network the fastest in the world.
The initial route is designed to allow trains of 400m in length and able to carry 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can operate on a London - Birmingham route.
A terminal that can accommodate 20,000 passengers per hour would be required.
Given space constraints, it is planned that an existing station will be expanded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Rail industry experts say only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should go ahead, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean a final decision will not be made before a general election.
Even if he starts the machine, the network will have to be built part by part.
Trains will initially be forced to run off high-speed lines on existing rails north of Birmingham, maintaining journey times between London and Scotland in excess of three hours.
This solution seems to be the best to ensure a transition from planes to trains, constituting a reference point for the rail revolution.
Taxpayers repay £75,000 loan for Tory orangery
Alan Duncan, the leading Tory MP, charged the taxpayer thousands of pounds a year to reimburse the cost of an orangery he built in his constituency home.
The party leader who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that members of parliament were being "maintained", increased his loan by £75,000 to build an oak extension to his second home, in Rutland.
He had been allowed to charge the taxpayer hundreds of pounds a month for the additional interest.
The Commons authorities received the complaints at that time and were not questioned by Sir Thomas Legg, who carries out a control of members' expenditure. Last night, Mr Duncan said the complaints could not be "clearer or simpler".
Mr. Duncan, one of the wealthiest members of Parliament, owns a two-storey house in a village in his riding of Rutland - Melton.
The neighbouring houses were sold for almost a million pounds.
The ground floor has a kitchen, living room and dining room, but the emoluments office says Duncan needed more space.
Last year, he added a veranda to the house, describing it in his plans as an orange grove.
Neighbors describe it as a "veranda for fun."
Mr. Duncan was not asked to explain the increase in borrowing during a recent investigation by the Commons Privileges and Standards Committee into its pre-borrowing provisions.
The Committee cleared him last month of any charges of non-compliance, following an investigation into his expenses.
In 2004, Mr Duncan changed the legal certainty of the GBP 271,406 loan from his London property to his constituency house which he bought in 1991, the year before becoming a Member of Parliament.
Documents released this week show Mr Duncan was claiming around £1,400 a month in loan interest until March last year.
In April, his applications increased by more than £1,800 per month.
The interest rate on Mr Duncan's RBS loan was not changed at that time, suggesting that all the increases were intended to finance the £75,000 loan.
The RBS variable standard interest rate fell from 7.94 percent in December 2007 to 4 percent in March this year, unchanged since then.
The latest release from the Commons authorities shows that Mr Duncan was still asking for £1,250 in May.
Mr Duncan lost his post as shadow chief of staff in September, after an undercover journalist allegedly filmed him saying members of parliament had to survive "on budget" after the spending scandal.
"In fact, it's now national, you have to live 'on budget' and you're treated like 'm... e"
He said: "I spent my money on my garden and asked for a small portion, based on what was okay.
And I could have asked for damn much more, but I didn't."
The MP, a millionaire from his previous position as an oil trader, began having to explain his expenses in May after it emerged that he had asked for thousands of pounds for his garden, before agreeing with the fees office that it "could be considered excessive".
An activist dug a £-shaped hole in Mr Duncan's lawn to protest after it was revealed he had been asking for £4,000 for three years.
Asked about the increase in borrowing last night, Mr Duncan said: "It was for major improvements, approved both by the fee office and then by Legg."
He added: "There is no problem of evasion or making or using rules or anything.
It was quite clear, in the rules, allowed, etc.
It couldn't be sharper or simpler."
Faithful, come and see the Brighton Advent calendar
Brighton's beach huts have found a new way to promote the winter months, an interactive advent calendar.
Beyond, an alternative church group that encourages spiritual exploration through creativity, invited 24 owners to decorate their cabins for each December day, using Christmas carols as a theme.
