Riot police immediately intervened unceremoniously.
In total, the police announced the arrest of 600 to 700 people, mainly according to them members of the "Black Blocs", these ultra-violent small groups that had distinguished themselves at the NATO summit in Strasbourg, in eastern France, in April.
The Climate Justice Action (CJA) coalition, one of the organizers of the demonstration, denounced the conditions in which hundreds of activists were arrested "indiscriminately", stressing that a hundred of them "were still held in the street Saturday night "handcuffed and kept in a sitting position despite the extreme cold".
Starting from Parliament, the procession, rather good-natured, took the direction of the Bella Center, site of the negotiations.
The demonstrators stopped about 500 meters from the building, without trying to enter.
A stage was set to welcome the scheduled speakers, before a candlelight vigil with the participation of the former South African Archbishop of Cape Town, Desmond Tutu.
The majority of the demonstrators had come by bus and train from major cities in Europe, but many Asians, including some Chinese and Koreans, were also present as well as Africans.
Nearly 3,000 people, mostly in sky blue raincoats, had formed a first rally in the morning in Copenhagen at the call of Friends of the Earth, who intended to form "blue tides" for "climate justice".
Today, we are taking to the streets to demand reparations for the ecological debt in favour of the South," said Lidy Nacpil, Filipino activist with the Jubilee South Coalition in Copenhagen.
We can not continue to say: we have time, said the Beninese singer Angélique Kidjo.
There are rivers that are drying up in Africa, streams where you can walk like never before.
For the first time in the history of climate diplomacy, born in 1992 with the adoption of the UN Convention, the alterglobalist movement has moved closer to environmental organizations.
French MEP José Bové, a figure of alterglobalism, explained that he had come to Copenhagen to "link climate justice and social justice": "Today, there is no break between the fight against global warming and the fight for another world".
The Asia-Pacific region, home to many islands particularly vulnerable to warming, kicked off the protests.
Some 50,000 people, according to organizers, had taken to the streets in Australia.
In Manila, a few hundred people, mostly students, marched in red, wearing bandanas touting solar energy.
In Hong Kong or Jakarta, but also in Canada, rallies of a few hundred demonstrators were also held to demand strong action against climate change.
In France, the events organized by the "350" network brought together a few hundred people, particularly in Paris, Marseille (south), Lille (north), Bordeaux (west) and Lyon (east).
In Geneva a few dozen people gathered.
Separatist Abkhazia elects its president, Georgia denounces a "farce"
Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, a little more than a year after Moscow recognized the pro-Russian separatist region of Georgia, while Tbilisi denounced a "farce".
Some 131,000 people were called to take part in this first election after the Russo-Georgian war in August 2008 for control of South Ossetia, another Georgian secessionist territory recognised by Russia.
Polling stations closed at 17:00 GMT.
Turnout was 58 percent hours before the close, according to officials from the Abkhaz Election Commission.
The first provisional results were to be announced on the night of Saturday to Sunday.
The five candidates running, including outgoing President Sergei Bagapch, categorically reject the idea of reunification with Georgia, which condemned the holding of the election.
These elections are a farce.
For his part, Georgian President Mikheil Saakashvili "regrets that Abkhazia has fallen under the total occupation of Russia," said his spokeswoman, Manana Manjgaladze.
Apart from Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory of 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world considers it a part of Georgia illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After separating from Georgia during the 1992-1993 conflict, which left several thousand dead, Abkhazia is seeking to show through this election that it is ready to join the international community.
This process is a step in our new life, our new era as an independent state," Svetlana Kvartchia, a 54-year-old historian, who said she voted for Bagapch, told AFP.
She was among voters who went to the polling station at a school in Sukhumi, the capital, in a pretty white building with a few palm trees in front of the entrance.
The question of Russian domination is at the heart of the presidential election in this region with sumptuous landscapes, on the shores of the Black Sea.
Large panels showing Bagapch alongside Russian President and Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev and Vladimir Putin are installed throughout this small territory of 216,000 inhabitants.
In Gali, in the west of the country, the head of the district, Beslan Archba, gave a warm welcome to the Russian officials who came to monitor the conduct of the election.
We, the Abkhaz people, are grateful, he said during a small ceremony, referring to Moscow's support, especially the decision to recognize the independence of Abkhazia.
I hope that your country will soon be recognized by the United Nations," Alexei Ostrovsky, a member of the Russian parliament, replied while raising a glass of vodka.
For its part, the opposition represented in the election by former Vice-President Raoul Khadjimba and two businessmen, Zaous Ardzinba and Beslan Butba, criticises the agreements concluded with Moscow last year, such as the one ceding control over the Abkhaz railways to Russia for 10 years.
The fifth candidate, Vitali Bganba, says he does not support either the current government or the opposition.
A majority of 50% plus one vote is needed to win the election.
If no candidate reaches this threshold, a second round must be held within two weeks.
