USA: a sarcophagus panel that belonged to Zola sold for 1.5 million USD
A Roman sarcophagus panel that belonged to French writer Emile Zola was sold Thursday $ 1.5 million, well above its estimate, announced the art dealer Sotheby's.
This front panel of two meters long by 63 cm high, dating from the third century AD, was estimated between 150,000 and 250,000 dollars.
The marble "representing four Dionysian scenes in a sophisticated architectural setting, surrounded by satyrs and bacchantes, is a rare piece, there are only four or five in the world," Florent Heintz, vice president of art auctions of Roman and Egyptian antiquity at Sotheby's, told AFP on Tuesday.
It was sold among a hundred lots.
The sale is still ongoing but this lot is certainly the one on which buyers have bid the most so far, told AFP a spokesman for Sotheby's, Dan Abernethy.
The discovery of the acquisition of this marble by Emile Zola dates back a few days.
The panel remained in Rome for nearly 300 years in the famous collection of the Borghese family, then appeared successively by the French actress Cécile Sorel, who had made it part of her bathtub in her Parisian mansion, and at Paul Reynaud, minister under the Third Republic in France and briefly President of the Council before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain.
There remained a gray area of about fifty years.
While searching the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz discovered that this panel was part of an "Emile Zola estate" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the fresco of "Rougon-Macquart".
