The UDF association raises its voice and calls on the New Centre to stop using its acronym
The UDF association, controlled by the MoDem of François Bayrou, reacted Friday to the attempted takeover bid of the president of the New Center, Hervé Morin, on the acronym of the former Giscardian party, by putting him on notice not to use it on any medium, under penalty of prosecution.
Hervé Morin publicly announced his intention to recover the acronym UDF, judging that François Bayrou did not deserve to defend his political legacy after reaching out to the left.
The Minister of Defense, whose party is a partner of the UMP, had also planned to confirm this strategy Saturday before the National Council of the NC.
To support his approach, he received the support of MP Hervé de Charette (former UMP switched to the NC) who claims ownership of the UDF trademark for having been the first to register it in 2004 at the National Institute of Industrial Property.
But Friday evening, the office of the UDF association, controlled by the friends of François Bayrou who do not intend to be dispossessed, came out of its silence to launch a formal notice to the minister and the deputy, urging them to no longer use the acronym and to transmit to them the ownership of the brand, under penalty of prosecution.
In recent days, you have multiplied the declarations indicating that you were going to propose to your political movement to +take back + the acronym UDF, writes the association in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the board, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem, as well as Senator Jean Arthuis of the Centrist Alliance.
You also saw fit to follow on your militant material and on the cover page of your site, the name of this movement, the +New center+, with the slogan +the UDF of today +, also note the signatories of the letter.
As you know, you have no right to the use of this acronym, explains the office of the UDF which puts in formal notice the NC to remove "immediately the mention of the name of the UDF from any medium as well as (its) website".
It also asks Hervé de Charette "to transmit the ownership of (the) brand to its legitimate beneficiaries".
If you did not, the courts would be seized to enforce the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members, the signatories warn.
In their letter, they specify that the UDF "has been a political movement in its own right since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends had "made the choice" to leave it in 2007 "to create a competing movement, as others had done in 2002, to create the UMP".
The New Centre therefore has, according to them, no right to use the acronym UDF (Union for French Democracy).
They also recall that the last UDF congress voted in 2007 to join the MoDem for three years and to create an office responsible for defending "the material and moral interests" of the party founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, continues the office, "when he filed the trademark", he was "no longer a member of the UDF for three years", but to the UMP.
He scandalously and fraudulently takes advantage of the absence of filing the acronym UDF to carry it out on his behalf.
This indelicacy, they denounce, before ironically on the strategy of the NC: "It seems to us that in politics, as in life, it is more worthy to make a name for oneself than to try to get out of anonymity by fraudulently taking a name to which one is not entitled."
Liliane Bettencourt case: François-Marie Banier will be tried for abuse of weakness
The court of Nanterre decided Friday to judge the artist François-Marie Banier to determine whether, as accused by the daughter of billionaire Liliane Bettencourt, he took advantage of a state of weakness of the octogenarian to despoil part of his fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his photos of stars, will be tried on 15 and 16 April 2010 for abuse of weakness, an offense punishable by a maximum sentence of three years in prison and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will be a trial in this case worthy of a saga about one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter tear each other apart while holding the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetics empire.
But the 15th Criminal Chamber also ordered that a medical expertise of Liliane Bettencourt, aged 87, should be conducted collegially by three doctors.
The heiress and main shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, at least not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre prosecutor's office during the investigation.
The designated physicians on Friday will have to submit a report before March 10, 2010, saying in particular whether Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness and at what times.
I think she will abide by it.
I will talk to him about it, said at the end of the hearing the lawyer of Mrs. Bettencourt, Me Georges Kiejman.
