This is excellent news (...) The expertise will show that he (Mr. Banier) manipulated this elderly lady who must be protected, he said.
For two years, the only daughter of Liliane Bettencourt has initiated criminal proceedings against François-Marie Banier, photographer and artist jack-of-all-trades, whom she accuses of having taken advantage for years of the weakness of her mother to obtain a billion euros in donations, in the form of checks, life insurance contracts or paintings of masters.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always denied having been manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a long-time friend.
While the court had to examine the admissibility of the action brought by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the pleadings of the lawyers sometimes turned to the big family unpacking Friday.
Thus, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer referred to three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the letter dated 2003, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I have never been able to talk to her since her marriage."
For its part, the Nanterre prosecutor's office again considered that the complainant was not admissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge refused in recent days to grant her request to open judicial protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to take legal action, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place," said the representative of the public prosecutor, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would rule once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it was formerly a question of imposing on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put market conquest strategies back in the right place. Although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors comes back regularly!
A demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, even more, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "demands of all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; It requires a commitment on the part of employees that the recipes of authoritarian management totally contradict.
This is why we are calling for a managerial revolution that would consist of putting employees at the center of the company's concerns in the same way as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I am afraid not.
- Firstly because I have been able to observe that, faced with a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do as a priority... which she has always done. !
- Secondly, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by American "neuroscience" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by research institutes and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to use the "levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, unsuited to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies presupposes the adoption of a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to realize part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from Motive Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life projects.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "in place".
They thus create a favorable ground for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: 'Just war' earns right-wing praise for Obama
The American right on Friday welcomed the speech given the day before in Oslo by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
Conservatives, who had ridiculed the awarding of the prize to Mr. Obama on October 9, applauded this time the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, former vice-presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said," Palin, the face of the Republican Party's right-wing muse, told USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the theme of "sometimes necessary" war in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is, of course, the last thing in my opinion the Americans want to have to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be stopped there, she said.
Obama, who inherited both wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way of explaining his decision to send 30,000 additional troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I thought the speech was really good, said the former speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential remarks.
In some ways, I found this speech quite historic," Gingrich told "The Takeaway" radio show.
The former congressman, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not give a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former pen of George W. Bush turned columnist at the Washington Post, Mr. Obama gave "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a bubble of security that they did not create and that they do not do much to preserve it", said Mr Gerson.
Among the few on the right who aren't convinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "dull, ampoulated and uninspired" on the National Review Online website.
To the president's left, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justify the use of force.
When war is wrapped in the notion of justice, one can easily justify the slaughter of innocent people, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained complimentary of the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely to Mr. Obama, called his speech a "blockbuster" even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression," the Californian daily said.
Mr. Obama "gave the right speech," said the New York Times, calling it "both dark and edifying."
Rover Scouts: Three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three marathon negotiating sessions, the road sector unions and TLF, the only employers' organisation to have stayed until the end, reached an agreement on Friday evening that puts an end to the strike slogan and the threat to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "delighted" by this agreement, after several sessions of negotiations, started Wednesday morning.
