Turkish judiciary dissolves pro-Kurdish party, decision with far-reaching consequences
Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday dissolved the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by angry protests in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision is likely to greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "hotbed of activities detrimental to the independence of the State and its indivisible unity", President of the Court Hasim Kiliç told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Ms Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's assets.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without labels.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party maintains however that it has "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organisation and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court's verdict comes as the government has reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, in an attempt to dry up Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had said a dissolution could lead to renewed tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
As soon as the court was announced, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP offices in Diyarbakir, the large city in the south-east populated mainly by Kurds.
The security forces fired tear gas canisters and used water cannons, while demonstrators threw Molotov cocktails or stones, with slingshots.
A hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Turk said the court's decision would "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning a party, he told reporters.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of parties.
It solves nothing, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
The move is a total torpedoing of the democratic opening launched by the government, political analyst Ahmet Insel said.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snows can fall
What Wolfgang Brauwburger wants is a harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearing and sanding service (FES) makes it clear that this is not to annoy citizens.
This is simply so that the agents can test the technique of the vehicles and learn to master them well.
And according to the meteorologists, it could well be for this weekend.
More than 300 officers and 120 vehicles are ready to tackle snow and ice.
The ESF follows a very elaborate plan here.
Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts snowing on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures drop below freezing, large blasting vehicles travel 20 main routes (called A routes).
This includes busy streets, main arteries, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire service accesses, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as Atzelbergstraße.
FES officers start their shift at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometers of roads must be salted with a road fondant that adheres well, in 3 hours of time maximum.
This is why the FES service starts at 3am "so that the roads are clear when the daily migration traffic begins".
Where it gets more difficult is when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the road clearing and sanding service "because no motorist is willing to let salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it is no longer snowing, access roads and service roads - such as Rat-Beil-Straße - are taken care of.
Side lanes and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger knows that this always causes some complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES pedestrian team sets out to clear priority areas deemed dangerous and passages.
As for cycle paths, the FES services generally cannot deal with them.
Mr Brauburger points out that there is a special service in Frankfurt which monitors the condition of the bridges between 10 p.m. and 4.30 a.m.
As ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
The police may also call on this special service when needed.
The birthplace of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long and 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull had sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended in sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in Thursday's Science magazine, Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to feature these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the land surface of the supercontinent, Pangea and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of early dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the ties of kinship, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt began excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Triassic.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations uncovered the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories concerning the early evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it Tawa after the word of the Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a truly exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery particularly spectacular, but he says that it confirms certain theories concerning the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the earliest dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, when saurians split into three major evolutionary groups: theropods (carnivores), which include the tyrannosaurus and velociraptor that appeared later and from which birds descend, sauropods, quadrupeds with long necks, and those related to them and ornithischian herbivores including species such as triceratops and stegosaurus.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting ratio of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found evidence that Tawa hallae has small air sacs in its bones at the skull, just like birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed air sacs and light bones, it can be assumed that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, researchers concluded that saurians appeared there.
As a result, the three major evolutionary lineages divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all the land masses that formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, the researchers argue.
Alan Turner of the Museum of Natural History in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silesaurus, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a mistaken view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while there are hardly any on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era, when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
In the Triassic period, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of present-day crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs spread all over the planet thus favoring the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction in which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or, dinosaurs were better adapted and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the flourishing of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since that time vegetated in the shadows: it was mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are those of professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
There are lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec City, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
