The new "Silicon-valley"
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under Soviet rule, a place of secret weapons research, under strict surveillance.
Today with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
Important places of production and research in micro- and nanoelectronics are located there.
As early as September 2008, representatives from Zelenograd established links with Riedberg, the place of science in Frankfurt – with the academic institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Center (FIZ).
There have been reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a "Protocol of Close Cooperation".
The signatories were Deputy Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz head of the Frankfurt project section.
In 2010 representatives of the FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will enable FIZ companies to enter the growing Russian market.
Russian scientific societies, on the other hand, want to obtain contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of famous Soviet research institutes and societies.
It is home to the Moscow Institute of Electrical Engineering, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The commune was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for weapons research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") takes its name from the forested hills in the heart of which the research centers are located.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be set high enough.
For its supporters it is nothing less than "the new heart of Europe".
If you will. S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, into a desperate chaos of construction sites for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
The head stations, with tracks that ended in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time of being the relics of nineteenth-century transport technology that acted as a brake shoe of modern rail traffic because it once took a long time to move locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that's what you have to do.
That is why the head stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart too: a passing station for trains, which is about halfway on the Magistrale Trans-European Rail between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava, hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realization of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 80s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners acknowledged that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
To tell the truth, the stations at the head of the line no longer pose any real problems of entry and exit since there are modern, reversible trains with railcars and pilot car at both ends.
However, the construction of Stuttgart 21 is now underway next to the new route of the inter-city line to Ulm.
Regional and communal policies prevailed.
The railway company is on board because it is the taxpayer who bears the brunt of the risks of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public company.
From an urban planning point of view, this project can be justified relatively well.
The result is an urban space that – if we believe the graphs of the computer-generated planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system, the S21 is harmful.
The passing station and the widening of the section are designed for human trafficking to which - and this is typical of the 80s - a huge growth was attributed.
At the time there was no competition from cheap flights.
Modern traffic policy should first focus on increasing freight traffic, because rail transport is much more environmentally friendly than lorry transport on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious, indirectly concerns many other railway projects.
For example, six billion euros are going to be swallowed up in the Swabian project.
That is the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion is more realistic.
One thing is certain, in the next decade this money will be lacking for other junctions and bottlenecks in the network.
The list of the Ministry of Transport lists a total of sixty major projects.
One of the most important is the widening of the section through the Rhine Valley by a good 180 kilometers.
Since 1987 this line has been built at idle.
It would be really urgent to press the mushroom all the way here.
But the S21 project has the effect of a braking shoe.
The Rhine Valley route is becoming the bottleneck for international freight traffic in the heart of Europe.
Government reviews airport ruling
In the Wiesbaden regional parliament, the Land government raised the possibility of appealing the judgment of the Hessian Administrative Court concerning the ban on night air flights.
