More than a footnote about Herta Müller
It is with these words "Arrived in Germany and it's beautiful, almost more control... " begins a work by the poet Werner Söllner, in which he thematizes in disturbing snippets of sentences, the experiences of a dissident who arrived in Germany who won freedom but at the same time lost his linguistic territory.
Werner Söllner, born in 1951 in Banat, Romania, was first a teacher of German and English in Bucharest and later a collection director in a children's publishing house before moving to Frankfurt am Main.
Söllner has received various literary awards; in 1993 he held the coveted chair of poetry at the Goethe University in Frankfurt and since 2002 he has been director of the Hessian Literature Forum at the Mousonturm Artist's House in Frankfurt.
He made a lot of headlines in non-literary circles last Tuesday, at a congress in Munich, whose theme was "German literature in Romania in the mirror and the distorting mirror of your Securitate files".
Visibly unsettled and embarrassed, Söllner made a statement in which he acknowledged to fellow German-Romanian writers such as Richard Wagner, William Totok, Franz Hodjak, and Helmuth Frauendorfer that he had collaborated as an informant for the Securitate political police.
Söllner received in 1989 the German Language Prize together with some of the participants.
Enlistment trials had begun insidiously in 1971.
I am, Söllner concludes, "therefore someone who has not sufficiently resisted the Securitate's attempts at intimidation."
The poet Werner Söllner is the informant Walter (IM Walter).
Almost simultaneously with the Nobel Prize honoration for Herta Müller and her exemplary literary quarrels with the mechanisms of power of the dictatorship, the literary scene is shaken and in particular the community of German authors from Romania, by a case that clearly shows the abyss and baseness of a political system, based on police surveillance and espionage.
Werner Söllner is, as far as current knowledge can tell, not only guilty but also victim.
In his own Securitate dossier, IM Walter played a role, writes literature scholar Michael Markel after Söllner's confession, and he refers to the positive influence of IM Walter who had interceded on his behalf.
"He was able to pull him out of all the difficult situations at the time," Markel said.
Markel felt the moral need to make this comment.
The form in which Söllner made his statement and in front of this audience was unexpected, however the admission of a former dissident of his collaboration with the Romanian secret service is in fact, not so surprising.
Germany is a pleasant reserve for Securitate spies, Herta Müller wrote in July in the newspaper "Die Zeit", after reading the 914 pages of her own dossier.
It can be assumed that the victims will have made speculations and will sometimes have guessed which real names were hidden behind the aliases Sorin, Voicu and also Walter.
Unlike Germany, where in the meantime consultation of Stasi files is a reliable process, the attitude towards the legacy of the Securitate files is still very confused.
Systematic clarification has been repeatedly thwarted and slowed down in past years.
It was not until 1999 that a national council corresponding to the Birthler institution was created to work on the assimilation of the archives of the Securitate (CNSAS) but the restitution of the files has rather dragged on since.
Since 2005, there has been a law defining the management of archives.
That the influence of former members of the Securitate in Romania is still very great is confirmed by the interview with a former official of the Securitate of Temesvar who, after the announcement of the award of the Nobel Prize to Herta Müller, spoke very dismissively towards the laureate.
She had psychosis, and in the end she was only questioned once.
The infamy of power thought it could be expressed here, without any gene, under the guise of freedom of expression.
Certainly, many inescapable questions are associated with the Söllner case as so often happens in a context of hidden guilt.
Why now? Who was robbed? The balanced reaction of the listeners, to Söllner's admission, gives hope that the rest of this chapter will be defined more by a thirst for knowledge than by accusations and a sense of shame.
On the genesis of the work of Herta Müller, who received the Nobel Prize yesterday, it is more than a footnote.
