The worlds of dreams
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only among the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between imagination and reality merge.
As long as these phenomena manifest themselves during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our darkened rooms, we can indulge in the wildest dreams and fantasies without hindrance.
However, the one who, awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the mentally ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, but sometimes prompts the boundaries between dreams, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can come in the most diverse forms, in the best case we call visions, at worst madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect stand out, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of neurotransmitters in the brain - first and foremost dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achetylcholine - breaks and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often manifest themselves during schizophrenic psychosis.
The earthly force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dreams.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of daydreaming; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
It was autumn 2001 when Henning T turned into a comic book character.
Its body is two-dimensional with garish colors.
The earthly attraction no longer has power over him, he hovers at the raz of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him winged devil creatures, grimacing, mouths bloodied, showing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Thunderous, nasty voices scream, coming out of walls and radio.
He can no longer stand these voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. rips two cables from his stereo, turns them into a loop and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a cabinet and passes the loop around his neck.
He jumps.
The loop is detached.
Let this serve as a lesson to you, shout the voices in a chorus to tear off his eardrum. "Go to a clinic and get treatment!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last of 2 years, the first of almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizoaffective psychosis, paranoid, in addition he is manic-depressive, he takes medication against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives; In psychiatric clinics it is the most common illness after depression.
In a crisis of schizophrenia, the people concerned can no longer differentiate between the inner world and the external world, they find themselves in a state of hyper excitement, which makes them suffer hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned in sensations.
Like dreams, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the Department of Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is right in the middle of the situation, everything has a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is as in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the possibility to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experience a hallucination once in a lifetime.
Unlike dreaming, according to Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis, is fundamentally preserved."
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real setting.
Why our brain does this kind of mess is always an enigma for researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to momentarily lose their perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies of twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
The researchers assume that those affected have minute brain damage.
It is assumed that neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But what still remains unexplained is how the abnormality of the neural system occurs and moreover the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain heats up.
The crazy thing, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others buy expensive drugs to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena for ten years: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The unreal world in our head".
Hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also of an impressive number of many other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression, but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
It is surprising to find that under certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions, are overactive or not sufficiently restrained; When our brain heats up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this state just like brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimuli, stress, heartache or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of participants admit to having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and she goes to high school.
A very normal girl actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and voices.
During recess, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long chestnut hair, speaks to him.
When she answers her classmates look at her, astonished – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think that this shy girl is a moody dreamer but Sarah K is not dreaming, she is sure.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She may even perceive his presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she finds this young person friendly.
Am I crazy?" she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this young person and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
Often the visions are heavy.
When she is in class, sometimes she cannot follow the class because the teacher is just introducing a new student in his eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is obviously explaining equations on the board.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for the sleep that comes too rarely and far too late, she often cannot distinguish if she is awake or already dreaming, if the images she sees, the grimacing faces or the girl with bloody gashes on her arms and legs are in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she shouts to these creatures.
She doesn't tell her parents or friends, they would think she's crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated last year and lives with her friend.
A year ago the hallucinations stopped.
Since she came into contact via the internet with the psychologist Kasten she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the likelihood is high that they will hallucinate after a while.
I guess the brain is not busy enough, so there is animation.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
