For Kasten, nocturnal dreams are also a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That's why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a special talent.
There is only one step between dream and hallucination.
In our overly consciously centered world, we unfortunately quickly tend to mistake imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the clinic for psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious illness, painful but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called dreamlike form of experience, a particular form of modification of consciousness awakened by dreaming.
Dreamlike experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is awake.
The dreamlike state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is in fact an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation that is in itself intolerable, a capacity for organization that is given to us, men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his dreamlike experiences in his book "Change of heart" as an action to safeguard the soul.
