75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women from younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fertility and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their professional careers limited because of motherhood.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of job held.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, start a relationship earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, postpone entry into life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women aged 35 to 49 with a permanent job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving into a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with stable employment have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment held largely influences motherhood, but less so the date of the start of cohabitation," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
Educational attainment is another factor widening the gap in the age of marriage between women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the later they marry and have their first child.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35- to 49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at an average age of 25.1 and 32.1, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those with elementary education marry and have their first child before finding stable employment, those with middle or higher education reverse this program and prioritize getting stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
