Emergency brake assist is now mandatory
As happened with ABS anti-lock braking system and as will happen with ESP stability control, emergency brake assist systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory for newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a waiting period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen pedestrian protection, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help avoid many rear impacts.
Emergency Brake Assist works by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system through the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always keep up the pressure until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers involved in an accident were unable to press the brake before the collision, and half of them did not take advantage of its full strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revancha, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is calculated that one in four accidents with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps him by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts the maximum force on the brakes to minimize damage.
