To design their latest and precious jewel, Porsche engineers started from the Boxster S and managed to slim it down by nothing less than 80 kilos, which leaves the balance at only 1,275 kilos.
This led them to do without, in the first place, the automatic roof which was replaced by a manual tarpaulin roof, allowing to reduce by 21 kilos, to use aluminum doors like those of the GT3, another 15 kilos less, to remove the air conditioner, 13 kilos, to reduce the gas tank from 64 to 54 liters,  7 kilos gained, to mount sports bacquets, another 12 kilos, and with light tires of 19 inches, five kilos.
Finally, they gave up the CDR-30 audio system, gaining another six kilograms and replacing door handles with fabric handles, saving the remaining kilo.
Although the model also exists with the dual-clutch PDK transmission, the test was carried out on a six-speed manual transmission model, mainly on secondary network roads in California, in the mountains, with particularly tortuous bends.
His behaviour can only be described as irreproachable.
The decrease in weight does not prevent the car from driving on the ground with aplomb.
On the contrary: it has been a long time since we tested such a small and light model that, at the same time, guarantees so much safety in corners, even at high speeds.
He is a small athlete, able to warm up his muscles at low speed for the necessary time, until we ask him to sprint, brake, recover and push his engine again...
That's what we wanted. Thanks to its steering, as communicative as it is precise, the car will do what our hands indicate on the steering wheel.
And she will do it with surgical precision.
Engine sound at will
The sound of its V6 boxer, with 320 horsepower (10 more than the Boxster S) is particularly successful and can be reinforced with the "sport" option or thanks to a system that modifies the roar of the engine, already used on the Panamera.
The acceleration capacity is brutal, whether stationary or during recovery.
The suspensions are firm, but not hard or uncomfortable.
The road surface we drove with the Boyxster Spyder was quite damaged, but the car handled potholes well.
The electronic assistants barely showed up all the way, while on some corners we found ice in the early morning and gravel later in the morning.
In short, an ultralight car, one of the most entertaining to drive and which is much more than a simple modification of the Boxster S.
The car will go on sale in February 2010, at a price of 70,831 euros.
