How much should you be paid based on your Facebook profile?
Facebook users can find out how much they deserve based on their profile, thanks to a new app from Trovit, the search engine with the highest number of real estate, job and vehicle classifieds in Spain.
The tool "How much should you be paid?" calculates users' salaries from more than 140,000 job offers available to Trovit in Spain, from a form available on Facebook, where you must register your profession, years of experience, age and the city where you want to work.
In the week that the application has been running, the search engine has detected that, as a rule, the Spanish worker "feels poorly paid," Trovit's product manager, Albert Ribera, said in a statement.
According to data available to Trovit from its search engines in the UK and France, Spaniards are the lowest paid.
A British computer programmer receives 45,226 euros gross annually and a Frenchman, 31,059, while a Spaniard receives 24,000 euros.
Similarly, a driver receives €34,247 gross annually in England, €25,751 in France and €16,420 in Spain.
According to Trovit, the lowest paid job in Spain is that of waiter, with 11,592 euros net annually, followed by that of salesman, with 14,725 euros, and that of worker, with 15,667 euros.
The most sought-after jobs on the Internet in the last three months are driver, part-time and social worker.
