Thank you very much
After rosy days since last spring, when asset inflation was the dominant note in the markets, uncertainty is once again arising, which is not surprising given their natural state, in an environment where agents are making decisions about an inherently uncertain future.
The remedy employed by central banks to stabilize markets has been to monetize debt through the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving abundant liquidity at near-zero rates, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilize.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been virtually finalized and, without questioning their maverick liquidity policy, are starting to put some sand in the wheels, as the ECB did, with their one-year auction next week.
As a result, investors doubt the ability of the global economy to sustain an economic recovery without heterodox measures, and we are seeing a reversal of the reduction in risk premia.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are rising again, although they remain far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
States have been forced to socialize private risk and public debt is again affected.
There is again a flight towards quality and the United States, Japan and Germany have been the safe havens chosen by investors, causing a widening of the differences between the countries of the euro area and Germany.
Spain was barely affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor'sa threatened with a further downward revision of the qualification of the Kingdom of Spain.
On the other hand, a little uncertainty is not bad for silencing moral hazard advocates, who were again trying to provoke a case of conscience among world economic policymakers who had curbed the destructive effects of credit limitation on job destruction, when what should be done was to declare a new Thanksgiving.
However, the situation in Dubai resembles a tribal struggle between the emirs to restore its place in power in the emirates and we have already seen the case of Greece.
A government that conceals a public deficit, elections, and a new government that discovers the pot of roses.
Prodi did it in Italy after Berlusconi and Socrates in Portugal after Durão Barroso.
It would be completely irrational for Ecofin to save Hungary from non-compliance with its external payments at the beginning of the year and allow a eurozone Member State to fail to meet its commitments.
What is logical, however, is that Ecofin has encouraged the Greek government to be transparent and makes its citizens jointly responsible for the need for extraordinary measures to maintain the stability of its public finances.
If, as we hope, we find ourselves faced with an episode of normalization of transitional risk premiums, after some excesses in high positions, this would be to be expected.
In the Spanish case, as long as our public debt spreads grow in line with European corporate bonds, we need not worry.
If European gaps were to narrow and ours continued to grow, then it would be a Spanish idiosyncratic risk.
The Standard & Poor's case is an anecdote. When our forecasting indicators force most research departments to anticipate their recovery models and revise upwards their forecasts for 2011, with the OECD and the European Commission coming back with a Japanese model for the Spanish economy, it does not bode well for their warning.
Again, this seems to be an excellent opportunity to buy Spanish assets, even if for the moment "prudence is the mother of safety".
