Their participation in the Champions League has brought in 476.4 million to Real Madrid and Barça since its inception.
The Champions League has become a source of income for clubs, since its birth in 1992.
Indeed, Real Madrid and F.C. Barcelona earned 467.4 million, which places them in third and fifth position of the clubs that have pocketed the most money in this competition.
Manchester United are at the top of the list.
Manchester United are at the top of the list.
Winning the UEFA Champions League doesn't just bring glory. It is also one of the main sources of income for the big clubs.
Indeed, the competition distributed 5,362.5 million euros to the 105 teams (including 12 Spanish) who have participated in the event since the creation of the tournament, during the 1992-1993 season, according to information from UEFA.
Real Madrid and F.C. Barcelona were well served in this distribution.
The white club was the third on the continent to receive the most money for its participation, and the only one, with A.C. Milan, to have won the trophy three times.
The Catalan club, current defending champions and last winners of the old European Cup in 1992, are fifth on the list.
At the top of the list are Manchester United and Bayern Munich, the two teams that, in addition, charged the most money for their participation in the last Champions League.
And this, despite losing to Barça.
On the other hand, Spain is only the third country, in terms of money brought in by the Champions League, although it has won more titles than any other (five, while Italy has won four, England three and Germany two).
Distribution
This apparent paradox can be explained by UEFA's complex procedure for distributing money.
For this year, the body chaired by Michel Platini plans to earn 1,090 million thanks to the Champions League.
Of this amount, UEFA will spend €413.1 million on fixed payments: each of the 20 clubs that participated in the classification matches (including Atlético de Madrid) received €2.1 million.
In addition, those who managed to participate received only 3.8 million to be there, in addition to 550,000 euros for each match played.
There is also a bonus in case of victory (800,000 euros) and tie (400,000 for each team). Those who reach the knockout stages receive three million each, the eight teams that reach the quarter-finals receive 3.3 million.
The last four teams will each receive 4 million.
And the champion will earn 9 million, against the 5.2 received by the other finalist.
Thus, under fixed payments, a club will earn at least 7.1 million, and a maximum of 31.2 million.
On the other hand, Barça pocketed 2.5 million for winning the European Super Cup in August.
But in addition, there are variable payments, to which 337.8 million are allocated.
This money is distributed according to the proportional value of each television market.
The Spanish market is one of the most important, and has four designated places.
The previous year's champion pockets 40% of the money allocated, 30% for the second, 20% for the third and 10% for the fourth.
The other part will be paid according to the number of matches played during the current year's edition.
