New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a loss are brought back to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage and the cost of repair.
Every claim is different, and calculating parts costs and labor time can be a long and complex job.
Calculating by hand the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labor can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the assistance of the latest computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
For this reason, almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Providers of claims assessment and maintenance services and solutions are dedicated to collecting information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other companies competing in the field of assessment tools and the development of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, so that in the last five years, more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car hits the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very difficult job, because you have to catalog each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and enter its price.
In addition, a "smart" graphic image of each model is created that can be clicked on the different parts of a passenger car.
If it is a massively sold model, the work can be ready in a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a low-selling automobile, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have, for example, information on Porsches, but not Ferraris or Lamborghini.
For vehicles on the road, the figure is over 99%.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centers around the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than one hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million annually to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million pieces of data are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this huge flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer different products.
The most common application concerns repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing breakage parts or to calculate the market or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that provides information on the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does in the United States.
Looking at the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an idea of the type of support it can provide to professionals in the sector.
The company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard claims assessment solution for adjusters.
It includes cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of parts, it takes into account repair times estimated by the manufacturer or paint schedules.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, a maximum of ten times a month.
Then, each insurance company, which carries out thousands of expertises, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the full identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it has rolled off the assembly line, only by its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle glasses, and AudaSubastas is a server open to the professional sector on the Internet that allows bidding on vehicles declared wrecked.
Its statistics service is very useful for identifying trends, performing geo-demographic analyses or knowing common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a given brand have gone to the garage for a breakdown or how many have suffered serious losses for a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It markets, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the manufacturer's official parts, prices and times.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971, as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of claims, breakdowns or car maintenance.
The GT Evaluation Guide is a historical reference product in the market.
The company works with 24,000 users in garages, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its business volume has grown at a rate of 20% per year over the past three years, and it made a turnover of 10.8 million euros in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it began its internationalization process, with the establishment of an office in Paris.
Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and established itself in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its turnover is generated in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. It works with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 garages, 3,000 of which are located in Spain.
Solera Group's worldwide revenue (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) will be $557 million, 3.3% higher than in 2008.
In our country, the company will receive 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was listed on the stock exchange for $1,000 million, today its shares are valued at a total of $2,400 million.
