Internet auctions of damaged cars
Last October, the Solera Group bought Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of damaged cars, motorcycles and special vehicles.
The transaction involved a cost of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the company's capital, which could expand next year to the remaining 15%.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This appraisal and sales service is aimed exclusively at professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, garages, junkyards and professional sellers who must be registered before starting operations.
This platform was founded in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations throughout Europe, including 500,000 in Germany.
Among its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently more than 1500 sellers and 4000 registered experts on the site.
It manages 3,000 ads per day and in the Spanish market, 100 new ads are published every day.
According to Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been removed can no longer be driven, but on the other hand, some parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
Classic cars can be re-registered, although they have been removed, after complex procedures.
Four-step garage quote
With the Auda-Taller tool, Audatex guarantees that the user gets a quote in just four steps: identify the vehicle, search for the spare part, create a quote and generate it.
Ease of use is an essential element of these systems, especially to convince older professionals who, to a greater or lesser extent, are reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, including 666 passenger vehicles, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Naturally, to use it, a computer and an Internet connection are required.
Once the model to be repaired is identified by its chassis number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and the necessary part is selected.
The user can include variables like labor price, mark-ups or discounts, and then they can print the quote to give to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a catalog of references.
The main difference between these two systems is that the one for garages does not include estimated labor times.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is 350 euros per year, which can be credited.
Currently, Audatex is working to make these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics see very positively, since it will allow, for example, to select a door and rotate it to see the inner side.
